article.headline: Xavier ties school record with 15th straight win
article.linkText: Xavier pulls away in second half to pound Temple
article.story: CINCINNATI (AP) -- Xavier's 96-65 victory Saturday had Temple coach John Chaney convinced the 11th-ranked Musketeers are headed for greatness. "This team is the best we've ever had in the Atlantic 10,'' Chaney said. Better than the Marcus Camby-led Massachusetts team of 1995-96? "This team is much better,'' Chaney said. "They've got all the ingredients.'' The basic ingredient is David West, who had 17 points, eight rebounds and seven assists after his jersey number was retired in pre-game ceremonies. "This kid's a great player,'' Chaney said. "He has a great sense of how to play this game. And he's patient. That's an aspect of his game that people don't realize.'' Romain Sato scored 29 points and Lionel Chalmers and West each had 17 for the Musketeers (24-4, 15-1), who tied a school record with their 15th consecutive win, matching the mark set in 1987-88. Alex Wesby had 24 points and David Hawkins added 20 for Temple (13-14, 10-6), which had won six in a row. "We were really clicking on offense,'' West said. "We stumbled out of the gate but turned it up.'' The Owls stayed even with Xavier for nearly a half before being overwhelmed by the inside-out style the Musketeers employ whenever West is being double-teamed. Sato and Chalmers were each 5-of-10 from 3-point range. "The whole thing was to attack, to get the ball right into the teeth of the defense,'' West said. Xavier shot 52 percent in the first half -- and 56 percent in the second half -- but didn't take the lead for good until Chalmers hit a 3-pointer that made it 29-28 with 6:24 left in the half. West made two free throws and a jumper to make it 33-30 and a basket by Hawkins brought Temple within one, but the Owls never got that close again. West made two more free throws, Sato hit a 3-pointer and a mid-range jumper, and Xavier had a 40-34 halftime lead. Consecutive 3-pointers by Hawkins and Wesby early in the second half brought Temple within three, but a dunk by West and consecutive 3-pointers by Chalmers and Dedrick Finn gave Xavier a 51-40 lead. West, showing all facets of his game, brought Xavier fans to their feet with a 3-pointer at 10:06 that gave the Musketeers a 64-45 lead. Throughout the soldout Cintas Center, fans held banners that read, "Player of the Year -- West.'' West is second to Xavier career scoring leader Byron Larkin and third to career rebound leader Tyrone Hill, and only those two jerseys had been retired by the school. When West's No. 30 was retired before the game, it was the first time Xavier honored a player that was before the end of his career. Xavier coach Thad Matta allowed West a final standing ovation when he cleared the bench with 2:13 left, and praised West's effort. "It was one of the best senior days I've ever seen,'' Matta said. "That's the most unselfish 2,000 points I've ever seen. To have seven assists today, that shows what kind of player he is.'' Temple played without assistant coach Nate Blackwell on the bench. Coach John Chaney said Blackwell had been suspended indefinitely for an unspecified violation of team rules.
